      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Key Insights\n\n**DTPA is an exceptionally powerful chelator** — its eight donor atoms (3 N + 5 carboxylate O) form highly stable complexes, generally ~1–2 log units stronger than EDTA for the same metal. The strongest binding is with Bi³⁺ (log β = 33.6), followed by Fe³⁺ (28.6), reflecting the preference of this octadentate ligand for high-charge, hard metal ions.\n\n**Clinically**, the Gd³⁺-DTPA complex (Magnevist®) is one of the most widely used MRI contrast agents, and Ca-DTPA/Zn-DTPA are FDA-approved for decorporation of transuranic elements (Pu, Am, Cm) — their enormous stability constants ensure the chelator can strip these metals from biological tissue.\n\n**The Irving-Williams trend** is clearly visible among the divalent ions: Cu²⁺ > Ni²⁺ > Co²⁺ ≈ Zn²⁺ > Fe²⁺ > Mn²⁺ > Ca²⁺ > Mg²⁺, consistent with crystal-field stabilization effects.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 16,
            "text": "### Key Insights",
            "claim_type": "filler",
            "metadata": {
              "classifier_strategy_version": "react-v7-schema-salvage-markdown-anchor",
              "classifier_round": 0,
              "classifier_stage": "initial"
            }
          },
